6.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes was born about 1212, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Nicholas de Morton. She died about 1291, in her hometown, at the age of 81."},"et":{"about 1212–about 1291":"umbes 1212–umbes 1291","1195–1259":"1195–1259","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1212–1291":"1212–1291","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","about 1291":"umbes 1291","1212":"1212","about 1212":"umbes 1212","1195":"1195","1291":"1291","Gresley Castle, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Church Gresley, Derbyshire, England":"Church Gresley, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1212–about 1291":"noin 1212–noin 1291","1195–1259":"1195–1259","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1212–1291":"1212–1291","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","about 1291":"noin 1291","1212":"1212","about 1212":"noin 1212","1195":"1195","1291":"1291","Gresley Castle, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Church Gresley, Derbyshire, England":"Church Gresley, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1212–about 1291":"environ 1212–environ 1291","1195–1259":"1195–1259","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1212–1291":"1212–1291","1